{
  "action": "schedule_routine_appointment",
  "escalation_tier": "none",
  "patient_message": "Hi! Thanks for reaching out. We'd be happy to get your annual physical scheduled for next month. We book physicals Monday through Thursday, between 8am and 4pm. Could you let us know which days of the week tend to work best for you and whether you prefer a morning or afternoon time? Once we have your preferences, our scheduling team will find an open slot and confirm your appointment. Looking forward to seeing you!",
  "rationale": "This is a routine, non-urgent request to book an annual physical. There are no symptoms, clinical concerns, or safety issues that require clinical review or escalation. The request can be handled through normal scheduling. I referenced the clinic's booking hours for physicals and asked for the patient's availability to move scheduling forward.",
  "evidence_used": [
    "ctx_hours: Clinic books physicals Mon-Thu, 8am-4pm.",
    "Patient message: request to book annual physical next month if there is an opening."
  ]
}

{
  "action": "request_clarification",
  "escalation_tier": "none",
  "patient_message": "Hi there! It looks like your message may have come through empty or didn't include any details. We'd love to help you. Could you please reply and let us know what you need? For example, you might want to schedule an appointment, ask about a prescription, share a symptom or concern, or get test results. If you are experiencing a medical emergency, please call 911 or go to your nearest emergency room right away. We look forward to hearing from you!",
  "rationale": "The patient's message contained only a period with no actual content or request. There is no information to act on, triage, or answer. The safest and most helpful response is to politely ask the patient to clarify what they need, while including standard emergency-care guidance in case the empty message was sent during distress. No escalation is warranted because there is no clinical content; if the patient responds with a concern, it can then be triaged appropriately.",
  "evidence_used": [
    "Patient message body: '.' (no substantive content)",
    "No clinic context provided"
  ]
}

{
  "action": "emergency_escalation",
  "escalation_tier": "immediate_emergency",
  "patient_message": "Sus síntomas —dolor en el pecho y dificultad para respirar— pueden indicar una emergencia médica grave. Por favor, llame al 911 (o al número de emergencias de su país) AHORA, o pida a alguien que lo lleve de inmediato a la sala de urgencias más cercana. No conduzca usted mismo. Si los síntomas empeoran, si siente dolor que se extiende al brazo, cuello o mandíbula, sudoración, náuseas o se siente a punto de desmayarse, busque ayuda de emergencia sin demora. Estamos preocupados por usted y queremos que reciba atención lo antes posible.",
  "rationale": "El paciente reporta dolor torácico agudo junto con dificultad para respirar, una combinación de síntomas de alarma (red flags) que puede indicar un evento potencialmente mortal como infarto de miocardio, embolia pulmonar u otra emergencia cardiopulmonar. Esto requiere evaluación de emergencia inmediata, no manejo a través de mensajería de la clínica. La respuesta dirige al paciente a servicios de emergencia y le da signos de advertencia adicionales a vigilar.",
  "evidence_used": [
    "Mensaje del paciente: dolor en el pecho ('mucho dolor en el pecho') y dificultad para respirar ('no puedo respirar bien')",
    "Pautas estándar de triaje: el dolor torácico con disnea son síntomas de bandera roja que requieren activación de servicios de emergencia"
  ]
}
